Associations between clinical variables and mutation burden in endometrial glands

Markdown file to present the methods to examine associations between clinical variables and mutational burden in endometrial glands. Before you start the following analyses, please convert the corresponding excel source data files to tab-delimited text files. The source data files are provided in our paper (Yamaguchi et al. Nat Commun in press).

Clean up workspace

rm(list=ls())

Load libraries

library(ggplot2)

Visualize linear relationship between age and mutation burden

p_age <- ggplot(mutBurd, aes(x=age, y=burden))
p_age <- p_age + geom_smooth(method="lm", level=0.95, color="black", size=0.5)
p_age <- p_age + geom_point(fill="#8dd3c7", shape=21, colour="black", size=5, alpha=0.9)
p_age <- p_age + ylim(0, max(mutBurd$burden))
p_age <- p_age + xlab("Age")
p_age <- p_age + ylab("Number of somatic SNVs\nper Mb sequenced")
p_age <- p_age + theme(
  legend.position="none",

  panel.grid.major=element_line(colour="#d3d3d3"),
  panel.grid.minor=element_blank(),

  axis.text.y=element_text(size=20, colour="black"),

Pearson correlation coefficients between clinical variables and mutational burden

name <- c("Age", "Cumulative number of menstrual cycles", "Menarche", "Parity")
clin_var <-c("age", "cum_num_menstrual_cycles", "menarche", "parity")
r_coef <- vector(mode="numeric", length(clin_var))
p_value <- vector(mode="numeric", length(clin_var))

for (i in 1:length(clin_var)) {
  clin_data <- mutBurd[, clin_var[i]]
  res <- cor.test(clin_data, mutBurd$burden)
  r_coef[i] <- res$estimate
  p_value[i] <- res$p.value
}

result_cor <- data.frame(
  clinical_variable=name,
  r=r_coef,
  p_value=p_value)

result_cor

# The significant association of parity seems to be due to confounding by age.

Linear regression model to assess effect of age on mutation burden

# We used the effect of age to calculate age-adjusted mutation burden
lm_univar_age <- lm(burden ~ age, data=mutBurd)
summary(lm_univar_age)
